<http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/LaboratoryAnalysisOperation> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Laboratory analyses are essential to deepen the characterization of materials present in MWFs, aiming to evaluate their potential for recovery or management." .
# 
# http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/LandImpact
<http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/LandImpact> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/LandImpact> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/EnvironmentalImpact> .
# 
# http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/LeachingOperation
<http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/LeachingOperation> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/LeachingOperation> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/MineralProcessingOperation> .
<http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/LeachingOperation> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "MWEI BREF : Extraction of soluble components from raw materials by the action of a percolating liquid (e.g. water). For example, gold can be extracted by heap leaching of a porous ore, or pulverised extractive waste from mineral processing. Other methods are tank leaching of ore, concentrates or extractive waste from mineral processing and in-situ leaching. Leaching may also be an unwanted process leading to polluted drainage (see \"leachate\"). Bio-leaching is a particular form of leaching involving living organisms"@en .
# 
# http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/LegalRestriction
<http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/LegalRestriction> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/LegalRestriction> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/Restriction> .
<http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/LegalRestriction> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Laws and regulations that may limit or condition recovery operations" .
# 
# http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/Level
<http:/purl.org/scimin-crm-mwf/Level> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
